RICHARD HOUGHTON
. I live at Bethnal-green. On the 2d of March, about half past ten o'clock at night, as I was returning home, (I was by the dead wall near Wilmot-street
), a person struck me a violent blow on my right cheek - I turned round, and saw the prisoner behind me - He is the man who struck me-it nearly stunned me; another man struck me on the other side, which knocked me down. The prisoner then put his hand into my right-hand breeches-pocket, and took my money. I made a snatch at his hand to prevent him, but he got it away. - He took two 3s. tokens, two 1s. 6d. tokens, and three shillings - He turned my pocket out, and ran away. I told him that I knew him well, and that he had got my money. I looked him full in the face. There were six or eight men standing behind me, beside the two who knocked me down - They all ran away together. A boy, named Arnes, came up to me while he was robbing me - I was laying on the ground-the prisoner was there when he came up-it was moon-light. I had been drinking at the Falcon, but was quite sober.

JAMES PAYNE. I am a clerk to the General Post-Office, in London. A letter addressed to a Member of Parliament (Sir
James Shaw
), would have been sent to the eleventh division. I was on duty on the 21st February, as a general sorter.
